Hurricane Floyd pounded the Bahamas with howling winds and blinding rain today, snapping palm trees in half, downing power lines and churning up dangerous surf throughout the vulnerable islands east of Florida.
Floyd's top sustained wind eased today to 140 mph -- down from Monday's 155 mph but still a Category 4 storm, the second most powerful designation for a hurricane.
At about 600 miles wide, Floyd dwarfed the small islands, its hurricane-force winds extending 125 miles from the storm's center.
